<div class="header">
  <div class="header-content">
    <div class="tag">Compiled by Gemini 3.1</div>
    <h1>Pfizer (PFE)<br/>Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A transparent, two-stage discounted cash flow valuation of Pfizer Inc. — using FY2025 actuals, disclosed assumptions, and one final number.</p>
    <p class="date">Updated {new Date().toLocaleDateString('en-US', {month: 'long', day: 'numeric', year: 'numeric'})} · Data: FY2025 10-K</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <!-- ═══ THE VERDICT ═══ -->
  <div class="verdict-card">
    <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
    <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${currentPrice.toFixed(2)} ({marginOfSafety}%)</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ KEY METRICS ═══ -->
  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(rev2025Val / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">FY2025 Revenue</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(fcf2025Val / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Free Cash Flow</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${eps2025Val.toFixed(2)}</div>
      <div class="stat-label">EPS (Diluted)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">{opMargin2025Val.toFixed(1)}%</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Operating Margin</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(netCash / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Cash</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — the gold standard of intrinsic valuation. No multiples, no comparables, no vibes. Just future cash flows discounted to today.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>Pfizer generated <strong>${(fcf2025Val / 1000).toFixed(2)} billion</strong> in free cash flow in FY2025. This is real cash the business produces after paying for everything, including capital expenditures, reflecting the post-COVID baseline operation level.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We grow FCF at <strong>4% per year</strong> for 5 years. This accounts for Pfizer's patent cliffs and pipeline replacements while modeling steady non-COVID growth driven by acquired products and existing blockbusters.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>2% forever</strong> — slightly below GDP growth, reflecting the continuous cycle of drug patents expiring and new approvals. We use the <strong>Gordon Growth Model</strong>: Terminal Value = FCF₆ ÷ (discount rate − terminal growth rate).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>8%</strong> — our required rate of return. This aligns with Pfizer's lower beta (defensive value stock). It's above the 10Y Treasury (4.18%) plus a typical equity risk premium.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash (${(netCash / 1000).toFixed(1)}B) = Equity Value. Divide by shares outstanding ({(sharesOutstandingVal / 1000).toFixed(2)}B) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. We're making exactly <strong>three</strong> judgment calls — everything else is math. Here's what we chose and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">4%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Pfizer is in a transition phase. Revenues plummeted after the COVID-19 vaccine/treatment boom. Now, with major acquisitions like Seagen and a focus on oncology and non-COVID base business, we model a modest 4% growth rate in cash flow as new drugs offset revenue losses from impending patent expirations (like Eliquis).
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">8%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        10Y Treasury: 4.18%. Equity risk premium: ~4-5%. Beta: Low (value stock). CAPM gives ~8%. We use 8% because Pfizer is a mature, defensive pharmaceutical giant. This means: "we demand 8% annual returns to justify owning this stock," which is lower than a volatile tech stock.
      </div>
    </div>
