  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Oncology dominance:</strong> Seagen acquisition unlocks massive potential in ADCs (Antibody-Drug Conjugates). Faster than expected integration and pipeline success could boost long-term growth above 4%.</li>
    <li><strong>Cost-cutting success:</strong> Pfizer has initiated a multi-billion dollar cost-cutting program. If they execute cleanly, operating margins could expand back toward 25-30%, driving FCF higher.</li>
    <li><strong>Surprise blockbusters:</strong> The model assumes average R&D success. A breakthrough in weight-loss drugs (GLP-1s) or another novel vaccine could radically alter the cash flow trajectory.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Patent cliffs:</strong> Eliquis (shared with BMS) and Ibrance face loss of exclusivity later this decade. If the pipeline fails to offset these lost revenues, growth could be negative.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt load:</strong> Pfizer took on significant debt to buy Seagen (Total debt is over $64B). The interest expense is real, and the net debt position pulls down the equity value directly.</li>
    <li><strong>Capital allocation missteps:</strong> If recent acquisitions do not yield the promised returns, the cash spent effectively destroys shareholder value long-term.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use an 8% discount rate for Pfizer?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Pfizer is considered a defensive value stock, often held for its dividend and stability in down markets. Its beta is historically low compared to the broader market. While tech stocks might command a 10-12% rate, an 8% hurdle rate is appropriate for a mature, cash-generative pharmaceutical company.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the free cash flow assumption only 4%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While tech companies might project 15%+ growth, big pharma faces a structural headwind: patents expire. Pfizer must constantly invent or buy new drugs just to replace declining revenue from older drugs losing exclusivity. A 4% growth rate implies they successfully replace lost revenue and eke out modest growth.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Does this include the dividend?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">A DCF inherently captures the ability to pay dividends. By valuing the total free cash flow the business generates, we are capturing all the cash that could be used for dividends, share buybacks, or debt reduction. Paying a dividend doesn't create new value; it just distributes the cash flow we've already counted.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

